name: 2,3,4-trinitro-toluene
Reason: The compound 2,3,4-trinitro-toluene has several functional groups that affect its melting point. The basic unit, benzene, has a melting point of 5.5°C. Adding a methyl group (toluene) shifts the melting point slightly up due to increase in molecular weight, around +3°C. Trinitro substitution introduces three nitro groups. Each nitro group significantly increases the melting point due to the introduction of strong intermolecular forces (hydrogen bonding and dipole-dipole interactions), as well as a significant increase in molecular rigidity. A single nitro group on a benzene ring can increase the melting point by approximately +30°C. With three nitro groups, this effect is additive and somewhat synergistic, so the increase can be expected to be more than 3 x 30°C. However, molecular symmetry and steric hindrance may prevent the full impact of the third nitro group, so the adjustment might be slightly less. Taking all these factors into consideration, an estimate for the three nitro groups could be around +80 to +85°C.
